2 HOUSE BILL 1544
1 WHEREAS, The State of Maryland recognizes the extraordinary bravery and
2 commitment of law enforcement officers who risk their lives to protect and serve the public;
3 and
4 WHEREAS, Law enforcement officers often face dangerous and life–threatening
5 situations in their duty to safeguard communities; and
6 WHEREAS, The heroic actions of Corporal Jeremy Herbert, Officer Garry Kirts,
7 Sergeant Paul Pastorek, and Officer Timothy Baublitz Sergeant Paul Pastorek, Corporal
8 Jeremy Herbert, Senior Officer William Kinsey, Officer Timothy Baublitz, and Officer
9 Garry Kirts during the collapse of the Francis Scott Key Bridge on March 26, 2024,
10 demonstrated unparalleled courage and selflessness in saving lives during a tragic crisis;
11 and
12 WHEREAS, The Maryland General Assembly seeks to establish a formal recognition
13 for officers who display extraordinary valor, sacrifice, and dedication to public safety; and
14 WHEREAS, The Maryland General Assembly also recognizes the tragic loss of life of
15 the six workers who perished in the Key Bridge collapse, whose sacrifices should be
16 memorialized; now, therefore,
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Public Safety
20 SUBTITLE 8. MARYLAND LAW ENFORCEMENT PUBLIC SERVICE MEDAL.
21 3–801.
22 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
23 INDICATED.
24 (B) “MEDAL” MEANS THE MARYLAND LAW ENFORCEMENT PUBLIC
25 SERVICE MEDAL.
26 (C) “SECRETARY” MEANS THE SECRETARY OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND
27 CORRECTIONAL SERVICES.
28 3–802.
29 (A) (1) THERE IS A MARYLAND LAW ENFORCEMENT PUBLIC SERVICE
30 MEDAL.

HOUSE BILL 1544 3
1 (2) THE MEDAL IS THE HIGHEST STATE HONOR AWARDED TO LAW
2 ENFORCEMENT OFFICERS FOR EXCEPTIONAL PUBLIC SERVICE, VALOR, AND
3 HEROISM.
4 (B) (1) THE GOVERNOR MAY AWARD THE MEDAL TO SWORN LAW
5 ENFORCEMENT OFFICERS IN MARYLAND WHO:
6 (I) HAVE DEMONSTRATED ACTS OF EXTRAORDINARY
7 COURAGE, BRAVERY, OR SELFLESSNESS WHILE ON DUTY;
8 (II) HAVE RISKED OR SACRIFICED THEIR LIVES BY SAVING
9 LIVES, PREVENTING SIGNIFICANT CRIMES, OR RESPONDING TO CRITICAL
10 EMERGENCIES; OR
11 (III) HAVE SIGNIFICANTLY IMPACTED PUBLIC SAFETY,
12 INCLUDING RESPONDING TO DISASTERS, TERRORIST THREATS, OR SIGNIFICANT
13 PUBLIC EMERGENCIES.
14 (2) THE GOVERNOR MAY AWARD NOT MORE THAN FOUR FIVE MEDALS
15 PER CALENDAR YEAR.
16 (3) WHEN AN OFFICER IS AWARDED A MEDAL POSTHUMOUSLY, THE
17 OFFICER’S NEXT OF KIN MAY RECEIVE OFFICIAL RECOGNITION AND
18 COMMENDATION ON THE OFFICER’S BEHALF.
19 (C) (1) A MEDAL REVIEW COMMITTEE SHALL BE ESTABLISHED WITHIN
20 THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND CORRECTIONAL SERVICES TO
21 EVALUATE NOMINATIONS AND SELECT RECIPIENTS FOR THE MEDAL.
22 (2) THE MEDAL REVIEW COMMITTEE SHALL CONSIST OF:
23 (I) THE SECRETARY, WHO SHALL SERVE AS THE CHAIR OF THE
24 COMMITTEE;
25 (II) THE SECRETARY OF STATE POLICE;
26 (III) ONE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE MARYLAND POLICE
27 TRAINING AND STANDARDS COMMISSION, CHOSEN BY THE SECRETARY;
28 (IV) ONE MEMBER OF THE SENATE OF MARYLAND, CHOSEN BY
29 THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE;
30 (V) ONE MEMBER OF THE HOUSE OF DELEGATES, CHOSEN BY
31 THE SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE; AND

4 HOUSE BILL 1544
1 (VI) ONE COMMUNITY REPRESENTATIVE WITH EXPERIENCE
2 WORKING IN LAW ENFORCEMENT OR PUBLIC SAFETY, CHOSEN BY THE SECRETARY.
3 (3) THE COMMITTEE SHALL:
4 (I) REVIEW NOMINATIONS SUBMITTED BY:
5 1. STATE AND LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES;
6 2. STATE AND LOCAL ELECTED OFFICIALS; AND
7 3. COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS AND CIVILIANS; AND
8 (II) ANNUALLY SUBMIT A LIST OF NOT MORE THAN FOUR
9 RECOMMENDED AWARDEES TO THE GOVERNOR FOR FINAL APPROVAL.
10 (D) A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY SHALL GRANT A ONE–GRADE
11 PROMOTION TO AN EMPLOYEE WHO RECEIVES A MEDAL.
12 (E) (D) (1) THE GOVERNOR SHALL PRESENT THE MEDALS IN AN
13 OFFICIAL STATE CEREMONY HELD ANNUALLY IN ANNAPOLIS.
14 (2) AT THE CEREMONY, EACH MEDAL RECIPIENT SHALL RECEIVE:
15 (I) A GOLD MEDALLION BEARING THE STATE SEAL;
16 (II) A CERTIFICATE OF COMMENDATION SIGNED BY THE
17 GOVERNOR AND THE PRESIDING OFFICERS OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY; AND
18 (III) A PERMANENT MARYLAND PUBLIC SERVICE HONOR ROLL
19 LISTING HOUSED AT THE STATE HOUSE.
20 (3) THE CEREMONY SHALL ANNUALLY HONOR AND REMEMBER THE
21 SACRIFICES AND CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE FOLLOWING WORKERS WHO LOST THEIR
22 LIVES IN THE FRANCIS SCOTT KEY BRIDGE COLLAPSE OF 2024:
23 (I) DORLIAN RONIAL CASTILLO CABRERA;
24 (II) CARLOS DANIEL HERNANDEZ ESTRELLA;
25 (III) ALEJANDRO HERNANDEZ FUENTES;
26 (IV) MIGUEL ANGEL LUNA GONZALEZ;

HOUSE BILL 1544 5
1 (V) JOSE MYNOR LOPEZ; AND
2 (VI) MAYNOR YASIR SUAZO–SANDOVAL.
3 (F) (E) MEDAL PRODUCTION AND CEREMONY EXPENSES SHALL BE
4 FUNDED THROUGH:
5 (1) AN ANNUAL APPROPRIATION CONTAINED IN THE STATE BUDGET;
6 AND
7 (2) GRANTS, PRIVATE SPONSORSHIPS, AND LAW ENFORCEMENT
8 FOUNDATION SUPPORT.
9 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
10 (a) The Department of Public Safety and Correctional Services shall convene the
11 medal review committee on or before September 1, 2025; and.
12 (b) (1) The first annual Maryland Law Enforcement Public Service Medal
13 ceremony shall be held on or before January 31, 2026 March 26, 2026.
14 (2) The following individuals shall be awarded the Maryland Law
15 Enforcement Public Service Medal at the ceremony held in accordance with paragraph (1)
16 of this subsection in recognition of contributions made during the collapse of the Francis
17 Scott Key Bridge:
18 (i) Sergeant Paul Pastorek;
19 (ii) Corporal Jeremy Herbert;
20 (iii) Senior Officer William Kinsey;
21 (iv) Officer Timothy Baublitz; and
22 (v) Officer Garry Kirts.
23 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
24 30, 2025.

